        <p>Recently, the tech team where I current work was unfortunately subject to redundancies. We're only a small team, and I know I was highly certain to be selected. It's never nice to lose your job, but at the same time, maybe it's a good time to start looking to see what else is out there.</p>
        <p>Firstly, I'm mainly a backend developer. I'm fairly confident with Javascript and Vuejs, but my CSS knowledge is terrible. This was something I was actively working on prior to any announcements. When looking through job adverts, one of my personal biggest turn offs is seeing "PHP Developer required - good knowledge of CSS/SCSS essential".</p>
        <p>I know enough CSS to get by, If given a pre-written template, or something from themeforest, I have a good enough working knowledge to make changes to make it look how I want. But what I struggle with most is all the edge cases. If the browser is this, then do X, otherwise do Y. If the browser is this but is lower than version 10, do Z, and so on.</p>

        <p class="page-title">The initial search</p>
        <p>With the current state of tech, there's also so much you need to know. You can't just get away with knowing a single language anymore. You need to know HTML, CSS, Javascript, Javascript frameworks and libraries (Vuejs / jQuery), frontend build processes, Npm, Yarn, ES6, Webpack, Babel, backend languages, backend frameworks, and then knowledge of CI/CD, AWS, Google Cloud, build pipelines etc.</p>
        <p>There's so much stuff you need to know. At companies I've worked for, there's usually dedicated people, or teams that handle different areas of the stack. Frontend Developers, Backend developers, DevOps. I have working knowledge of what all these things are - I can put together a really basic deployment pipeline with github and digital ocean, but trying to understand everything is often to much.</p>
        <p>And I think thats one of the problems with job adverts lately. Companies are so focussed on trying to get a developer who can do it all, rare as those might be, that often the developer with a basic working knowledge of the tech pass by. I saw a few adverts which I would have probably applied for, if there was less requirements to having expert knowledge of a whole stack.</p>
        <p>That being said, I know what I need to learn. A lot of the jobs I passed by needed CSS. I'll work on that, and I have done with this site. I haven't build a site from scratch in a long time, so forcing myself to work with CSS (via Tailwind) felt like a good practical exersize.</p>
        <p>And obviously my new site is going to deployed, so will hopefully revisit build pipelines.</p>

