        <p class="page-title">The coding tests</p>
        <p>Whats a tech interview without a coding test! I personally have quite enjoyed the coding tests I've had over the years. It gives me a chance to see how far I've come from the first coding test I ever did. I get to apply all the knowledge I've gained from previous positions, into a single purposeful feature.</p>
        <p>Both tests I got to do at home, and was given a weekend for one, and a day for another. Both of which I pulled all-nighters on. I'm typically a night owl anyway. I have a really nice view from my front room window out to sea, and there's something about everything being quiet, at night, no cars, sea view, which some netflix series on in the background that really helps me concentrate.</p>
        <p>I wouldn't say the tests were hard, one needed me to implement some filesystem logic, and the other required me to build up a complete dataset by querying 2 endpoints on a unreliable REST api. Both of the challenges are on my github. <a href="https://github.com/philcross/catstorage" target="_blank" class="text-blue hover:text-blue-darker no-underline">https://github.com/philcross/catstorage</a> and <a href="https://github.com/philcross/itccompliance" target="_blank" class="text-blue hover:text-blue-darker no-underline">https://github.com/philcross/itccompliance</a>.</p>
        <p>I really enjoyed the test in the second link. One of the requirements was to build the application without any framework. I've worked with frameworks like Laravel for years now, they do all the hard work, so actually deciding the best way to approach the task, without the framework was quite fun.</p>

        <p class="page-title">The interviews</p>
        <p>The tests must have been pretty good, because I was invited for interviews for both of them. I'm an introvert, and like probably most developers have a degree of impostor syndrome. I try to push myself into giving demo's of project work when I can, but I still get pretty sweaty and shaky with nerves!</p>
        <p>I really don't enjoy being interviewed. There's so much pressure, even more so when you don't have the security of if the interview doesn't go well, you can just go back to your current job. I've been pretty lucky throughout my career. Most of my interviews have gone pretty well, and I think most of that success is due to a high level or preparation.</p>
        <p>A couple of days before the interview, I'll open up an editor, and jot down every possible thing I can think of they might ask. Why I'm looking for a new job? What are my strengths? What are my weaknesses? What do I know about the company? I try to do a lot of preparing for each interview, and thats been super beneficial. It let's me forget about questions I haven't prepared for. I'm not scrambling my brain for questions I know the answer to.</p>
        <p>The Bristol interview, which was done via Skype, I thought went really well, and it must of done as I was offered the job. The bournemouth one I'm not too sure about. I had to drive to their offices, which were about 2.5 hours away (5 hours total drive). The offices were the most impressive offices I've seen. They were really awesome. The tech they were making was really awesome, and the company as a whole felt like it wouuld be a great company to work for.</p>
